1.               Project introduction:

House price is always a hot topic. When you are hunting for house, you will spend a huge amount of money. You may deposit for a long time to make the down payment and you need to make a loan for 30 years. So that’s why the house price is very important and sensitive. For your future dream house, expected relax place, and a feasible payment plan, to estimate the house price ahead of time is helpful. But when you are reviewing the information of the house, a lot of parameters(predictors) appear. As the common sense, the street(location), lot size is the most important predictors. How about the others? 

In this project firstly, I did some data cleaning, and data visualization. Then I built statistical models based on the past sale data and the relative predictors. And I used the models to predict the house sale price with the test data. When I am building the models, I tried to find which predictor has relationship with house price, what is the relationship between the predictor. The purpose to estimate f is both prediction and inference.

From the models’ comparison, KNN (k=1) is the best model to predict the house price. It means: if you want to estimate a house’s sale price, try to find a sold house which is similar.

 

2.              Data Entry

The data is I use in this project is Ames Housing dataset. It was compiled by Dean De Cock for use in data science education. It can be download here: https://www.kaggle.com/c/house-prices-advanced-regression-techniques/data?select=train.csv

From the website, the files include:

File Name

Explanation

train.csv

the training set

test.csv

the test set

data_description.txt

full description of each column, originally prepared by Dean De Cock but lightly edited to match the column names used here

Form 1. Data files name and explanation

The data has 1460 house sale records in train data and 1459 house sale records in test data. In train data, it has 1461 rows. The first row is the title, and below each row represents a house sale record. Each house record has house sale price and 80 predictors including lot size, house style, street, year built, roof style, month sold, year sold….

Below is some of the variables name and description.

Form 2. Data variables name and description

3.              Data cleaning

The first column is id, I just simply deleted it.

I found some variables has only one level. Or some variables are almost all “NA”. Or some categorical variables have large percentage on one of the categories, and small percentage on the others. And I checked the box plotting, there is not such an obviously difference between the categories. To avoid cannot found the minor category in training set error, I delete these categorical variables. For example, I deleted these variables: Alley, Street, LotFrontage ….

Also, I combined some categories(level<10) of some variables to avoid cannot found the minor category in training set error.

5.              Model selection

Before building model, I split train.csv 75% to training data and 25% to testing data. All the models are built using training data, and the prediction was made using testing data.

a. Simple Linear Regression

I started with simple linear regression. After I built first model, when I use summary(), I found two variables’ value are NA. This is because they are correlated with other variables. I deleted these two variables: TotalBsmtSF and GrLivArea. Deleting these variables will not cause R^2 or MSE change.

I use two linear regression models: both quantitative and qualitative variables, only qualitative variables. Using both quantitative and qualitative variables can give a better prediction, but for simple linear regression, the MAE is large, and R square is low.

 

MSE

R square

Form 3. Simple linear regression prediction

b. Multiple linear regression

I simply used OverallQual^2 to make the multiple linear regression, the other variables are the same with simple linear regression. Multiple linear regression did not improve linear regression prediction much. The results are totally the same.

c. KNN Regression

I choose k=1,3,5 to build KNN model. I found KNN regression has a lower MAE and high R square. And for k, the smallest k=1 has the best performance. However, k=1, 3, 5 the results are in the same magnitude. All of them gave a better prediction than the other regression models.

d. Shrinkage variable selection using Ridge method

By adding a shrinkage penalty term: , Ridge regression model introduced the tuning parameter   which has the effect of shrinking the estimates of βj towards zero. Ridge regression's advantage over least squares is because it has bias-variance trade-off. When λ increases, the fexibility of the ridge regression decreases, the variance decreased and the bias increased.

I use CV to select best λ. Best λ is 28427.95. And compared to linear regression, Ridge improved the prediction a lot. But it is still not so good than KNN regression.

Figure 10. Ridge λ and MSE plot

e. Shrinkage variable selection using Lasso method

Lasso is similar to Ridge. The difference is penalty term is: .

I use CV to select best λ. Best λ is 809.6383. It performed almost the same level with Ridge. Ridge’s prediction is slight better than Lasso.

Figure 11. Lasso λ and MSE plot

f. Forward stepwise subset selection

I got when number of variables is 33, BIC is smallest. I used these 33 variables to build linear model, and got a lower MAE model. However, it didn’t improve much comparing to simple linear model.

 

Figure 12. Forward stepwise subset selection

g. Backward stepwise subset selection

I got when number of variables is 44, BIC is smallest. I used these 44 variables to build linear model, and got a lower MAE model. However, it didn’t improve much comparing to simple linear model.

 

Figure 13. Backward stepwise subset selection

h. Tree

Firstly, I generated a tree with 12 terminal nodes. Then I use CV to find the best number of terminal nodes(size). I got when tree size equal to 9, the deviation is the smallest. I use size 9 to prune the tree. After prune the tree, the prediction and R square is better, but the improvement is not so much. It is the same level with the original tree.

Figure 14. Tree deviation and size plot                                      Figure 15. Pruned tree

6.              Conclusion

House price depends on a lot of variables.

Some predictors have positive relationship (positive coefficients) with SalePrice, such as OverallQual, OverallCond, LotArea, YearBuilt. In general words, this means, the bigger, better condition, more quality material, and new built would make a higher sale price.

From Form 5, KNN k=1 is the best model. It means: if you want to estimate a house’s sale price, try to find a sold house which is similar. At the end, I used the KNN, k=1 and used all training data to make the model, and do prediction on the test data.

In this project, simple linear model performed the worst. Using multiple linear regression, subset selection can improve a little. Using tree regression is better. Using Lasso and Ridge can improve the prediction a lot comparing to the previous models. And KNN is the best model in this project.

In Form 5, I use MSE, MAE, R square to compare the prediction result. The definition of MSE, MAE and R squre is as below.

MSE: Mean squared error

MAE: Mean absolute error

R square:

RSS: Residual sum of squares

TSS: total sum of squares

: real value   : estimated value

levels(data$MSZoning)

## [1] "C (all)" "FV"      "RH"      "RL"      "RM"

levels(data$MSZoning)[levels(data$MSZoning)%in%c("C (all)","RH")] <- "CandRH" #combine C and RH
levels(data$LotConfig)[levels(data$LotConfig)%in%c("FR3","FR2")] <- "FR2andFR3"
levels(data$RoofStyle)[levels(data$RoofStyle)%in%c("Shed","Mansard","Gambrel")] <- "Combined"
levels(data$RoofMatl)[levels(data$RoofMatl)%in%c("Tar&Grv","WdShngl","WdShake","ClyTile","Membran","(Other)","Metal","Roll")] <- "Combined"
levels(data$ExterCond)[levels(data$ExterCond)%in%c("Ex","Po","Fa")] <- "CombinedFa"
levels(data$Foundation)[levels(data$Foundation)%in%c("Slab","Stone","Wood")] <- "FR2andFR3"
levels(data$HeatingQC)[levels(data$HeatingQC)%in%c("Po","Fa")] <- "CombinedFa"
levels(data$Electrical)[levels(data$Electrical)%in%c("FuseP","Mix","FuseF")] <- "CombinedFuseF"
levels(data$Functional)[levels(data$Functional)%in%c("Maj2","Sev","Maj1")] <- "CombinedMaj1"
levels(data$SaleType)[levels(data$SaleType)%in%c("ConLD","ConLI","ConLw","(Other)")] <- "CombinedOther"
levels(data$SaleCondition)[levels(data$SaleCondition)%in%c("AdjLand","Alloca")] <- "CombinedFa"
levels(data$Exterior2nd)[levels(data$Exterior2nd)%in%c("AsphShn","Brk Cmn","CBlock","ImStucc","Other","Stone")] <- "CombinedOther"

levels(testData$HeatingQC)[levels(testData$HeatingQC)%in%c("Po","Fa")] <- "CombinedFa"
levels(testData$Electrical)[levels(testData$Electrical)%in%c("FuseP","Mix","FuseF")] <- "CombinedFuseF"
levels(testData$Functional)[levels(testData$Functional)%in%c("Maj2","Sev","Maj1")] <- "CombinedMaj1"
levels(testData$SaleType)[levels(testData$SaleType)%in%c("ConLD","ConLI","ConLw","(Other)")] <- "CombinedOther"
levels(testData$SaleCondition)[levels(testData$SaleCondition)%in%c("AdjLand","Alloca")] <- "CombinedFa"
levels(testData$Exterior2nd)[levels(testData$Exterior2nd)%in%c("AsphShn","Brk Cmn","CBlock","ImStucc","Other","Stone")] <- "CombinedOther"
